last couple of years.

00:06:55.720 --> 00:06:57.080
&gt;&gt; Sarah Burnes: He writes
wonderfully about walking.

00:06:57.080 --> 00:07:02.730
&gt;&gt; Craig Mod: So in Japan I live
mainly in Tokyo and Japan has a lot

00:07:02.730 --> 00:07:05.100
of beautiful pilgrimage
walks that are, you know,

00:07:05.100 --> 00:07:07.890
these paths that are a thousand
years old or 1200 years old,

00:07:07.890 --> 00:07:09.450
and they're really accessible,

00:07:09.450 --> 00:07:11.000
and they're really
easy to do these walks.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:14.410
And I've done 10 or 11
in the last three years.

00:07:14.410 --> 00:07:18.110
And the last one I did was
just two weeks ago and I pulled

00:07:18.110 --> 00:07:22.530
out Dan Rubin who's a great
photographer and another friend

00:07:22.530 --> 00:07:25.300
of mine, and the three of us
did this walk for eight days

00:07:25.300 --> 00:07:27.260
and it's called [foreign words].

00:07:27.260 --> 00:07:30.490
It's one of the old
pilgrimage routes.

00:07:30.490 --> 00:07:33.740
And the goal was -- Dan and I
had wanted to do a book together

00:07:33.740 --> 00:07:36.940
for a while, a photography
kind of collection,

00:07:36.940 --> 00:07:38.670
and I said, all right, Dan.

00:07:38.670 --> 00:07:42.080 position:56%
Let's do this walk and then we're
going to hide in a house for a week,

00:07:42.080 --> 00:07:45.310
this house in the countryside
that a friend of mine lent to us.

00:07:45.310 --> 00:07:48.250
It was old, it was freezing,
it was a 150-year-old sort

00:07:48.250 --> 00:07:54.520
of Meiji era Japanese sort of
mayor's house that was kind

00:07:54.520 --> 00:07:56.450
of converted, being
converted into an inn.

00:07:56.450 --> 00:07:58.090
