just a download.

00:30:37.850 --> 00:30:39.150
It's so effortless.

00:30:39.150 --> 00:30:45.640
But more than any other community
I've seen the photography community

00:30:45.640 --> 00:30:47.310
embrace the PDF.

00:30:47.310 --> 00:30:51.730
It's like a true book, a true book
of like how to do photography.

00:30:51.730 --> 00:30:54.530
&gt;&gt; Virginia Heffernan: Let me
tell you like a weird thing

00:30:54.530 --> 00:30:59.130
about making books valuable again,
making content valuable again.

00:30:59.130 --> 00:31:05.770
ACQUITY, the insurance company,
a couple of years ago decided

00:31:05.770 --> 00:31:09.060
that they were going to
publish their annual report

00:31:09.060 --> 00:31:10.760
in a pop-up book.

00:31:10.760 --> 00:31:15.830
And pop-up books, including <i>Pat the
Bunny </i>and the massed produced ones,

00:31:15.830 --> 00:31:18.020
all are made by hand.

00:31:18.020 --> 00:31:21.290
There's no way -- I mean, they
make them in China but each one --

00:31:21.290 --> 00:31:24.070
there's no machine
technology involved.

00:31:24.070 --> 00:31:25.670
And what they did -- what it did,

00:31:25.670 --> 00:31:29.290
because all the other annual
reports were circulated digitally,

00:31:29.290 --> 00:31:33.500
some in PDFs and so forth,
was they created demand

00:31:33.500 --> 00:31:35.660
for their annual report.

00:31:35.660 --> 00:31:41.090
And they'd had a great year and
all of a sudden everyone wanted

00:31:41.090 --> 00:31:45.060
to get their hands on the
ACQUITY Annual Report.

00:31:45.060 --> 00:31:48.070
I mean, it was like, you know,
at some insurance whatever.

00:31:48.070 --> 00:31:49.670
It was the talk of the whole thing.

00:31:49.670 --> 00:31:54.520 position:56%
And, you know -- and I also recently
talked to the lawyer for Scholastic

00:31:54.520 --> 00:31:57.170
who kept the last J. K.
Rowling thing offline

00:31:57.170 --> 00:31:58.850
until the release last
-- <i>Harry Potter </i>novel.

00:31:58.850 --> 00:32:03.500
And it meant she had to be in like,
I don't know what they call them.

00:32:03.500 --> 00:32:06.480
It's like the equivalent of clean
rooms or rubber rooms or something,

00:32:06.480 --> 00:32:11.110
where there's no WiFi and they
had to like create computers

00:32:11.110 --> 00:32:14.330
and printers and stuff that
never -- and no phones.

00:32:14.330 --> 00:32:17.400
Nothing could have any WiFi access.

00:32:17.400 --> 00:32:20.890
So it's like creating the
edges, creating the margins,

00:32:20.890 --> 00:32:24.440
creating the like -- there can
only be 40 of these pop-up books.

00:32:24.440 --> 00:32:26.120
And like you will, there
will never be a 50th.

00:32:26.120 --> 00:32:29.200
And even if you took flat photos
of it, even if you whatever,

00:32:29.200 --> 00:32:30.500 position:56%
you can't make another one of these.

00:32:30.500 --> 00:32:31.800
&gt;&gt; Craig Mod: Right.

00:32:31.800 --> 00:32:33.100
Well, and I think the
proliferation of the infinitude

00:32:33.100 --> 00:32:34.400
of the Internet has made these
things even more compelling, right?

00:32:34.400 --> 00:32:35.700 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Virginia Heffernan: Right, right.

00:32:35.700 --> 00:32:37.000
&gt;&gt; Craig Mod: And that's
why I mean with our --

00:32:37.000 --> 00:32:38.300
this photo book, for example, it's
like we can put most of the photos

00:32:38.300 --> 00:32:39.600
up on Instagram but
without those edges.

00:32:39.600 --> 00:32:40.900
And also just seeing photos big --

00:32:40.900 --> 00:32:42.200
&gt;&gt; Virginia Heffernan: Yeah.

00:32:42.200 --> 00:32:43.500
&gt;&gt; Craig Mod: -- is sort of
compelling in and of itself.

00:32:43.500 --> 00:32:44.800
&gt;&gt; Virginia Heffernan: Yeah, yep.

00:32:44.800 --> 00:32:46.100
&gt;&gt; Craig Mod: Without
the edges, I don't know.

00:32:46.100 --> 00:32:47.400 position:56%
It's somehow -- I think people don't
take the time to really look at it.

00:32:47.400 --> 00:32:48.700
&gt;&gt; Virginia Heffernan: Yeah.

00:32:48.700 --> 00:32:50.000
&gt;&gt; Craig Mod: To really
give it a moment.

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:51.300
And so a pop-up book is --

00:32:51.300 --> 00:32:52.600
&gt;&gt; Virginia Heffernan:
A good call, right?

00:32:52.600 --> 00:32:53.900
&gt;&gt; Craig Mod: -- a super-powerful
way of doing that, yeah, yeah.

