00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:04.300
&gt;&gt; One of the first things
that attracted me to the work

00:33:04.300 --> 00:33:05.600
of Craig was his fascination
with Japan, living in Japan.

00:33:05.600 --> 00:33:06.900
And one of the things that
bothers me about the Internet is

00:33:06.900 --> 00:33:08.200
that you're always worried --

00:33:08.200 --> 00:33:09.500
[ Inaudible Speaker ]

00:33:09.500 --> 00:33:10.800
-- you're going to see the
Internet in a different way.

00:33:10.800 --> 00:33:12.100
So I wanted Craig to
talk a little bit

00:33:12.100 --> 00:33:13.400
about what does the Internet look

00:33:13.400 --> 00:33:14.700
like for a young person
in Japan right now?

00:33:14.700 --> 00:33:16.000 position:56%
What are they doing on social media?

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:17.790
What types of things
are they reading,

00:33:17.790 --> 00:33:19.470
from a literary perspective?

00:33:19.470 --> 00:33:21.210 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Virginia Heffernan: From Myanmar.

00:33:21.210 --> 00:33:22.510
&gt;&gt; Craig Mod: Well,
or Myanmar, yeah.

00:33:22.510 --> 00:33:24.960
I just spent two months in
Myanmar at the end of last year.

00:33:24.960 --> 00:33:28.340
Myanmar's fascinating just
because two years ago a SIM

00:33:28.340 --> 00:33:34.410
for a cellphone cost $5000-ish, and
last year it went down to $1.50.

00:33:34.410 --> 00:33:36.080
So it's a pretty big drop.

00:33:36.080 --> 00:33:37.770
And then they opened up --

00:33:37.770 --> 00:33:41.270 position:56%
the government realized being a
military dictatorship wasn't helping

00:33:41.270 --> 00:33:43.260
them much and they
started opening up markets.

00:33:43.260 --> 00:33:45.800
Now there's 3G coverage
kind of all over the place.

00:33:45.800 --> 00:33:47.100
And you have a bunch
of farmers sitting

00:33:47.100 --> 00:33:51.770
on buffalo playing Clash Your Clans
[laughter] which is kind of cool.

00:33:51.770 --> 00:33:53.070
Japan is funny, right?

00:33:53.070 --> 00:33:54.790
I mean Japan -- a lot of times when
people talk about Japan and things

00:33:54.790 --> 00:33:57.640
that come out of Japan, there's
this Galapagos phrase that's

00:33:57.640 --> 00:33:58.940
thrown around.

00:33:58.940 --> 00:34:01.900
The Galapagos keitei,
the Galapagos cellphones.

00:34:01.900 --> 00:34:04.830
You know, Japan, if you went
to -- I moved to Japan in 2000.

00:34:04.830 --> 00:34:06.610
You know the first cell
phone I got had a camera.

00:34:06.610 --> 00:34:09.550
It was a color screen, it
was this clamshell thing.

00:34:09.550 --> 00:34:11.330
I mean it felt magical.

00:34:11.330 --> 00:34:13.560
I mean it really -- like there's
nothing else in the world like it.

00:34:13.560 --> 00:34:16.340
And none of those cell phones
were exported because none

00:34:16.340 --> 00:34:20.510
of them were built to work on, you
know, global sort of cell networks.

00:34:20.510 --> 00:34:22.020
It could only work in Japan.

00:34:22.020 --> 00:34:23.570
A lot of the functionality
they built

00:34:23.570 --> 00:34:25.710
for it was only workable in Japan.

00:34:25.710 --> 00:34:27.120
You could, you know, you
could use a cell phone to pay

00:34:27.120 --> 00:34:28.630
for stuff at convenience stores.

00:34:28.630 --> 00:34:29.930
But, of course, it
only worked in Japan.

00:34:29.930 --> 00:34:31.290
It was all proprietary protocols.

00:34:31.290 --> 00:34:33.130
The Internet on those
phones was called,

00:34:33.130 --> 00:34:34.950
the DOCOMO Network
was called i-Mode,

00:34:34.950 --> 00:34:36.880
so you weren't accessing
the open Internet.

00:34:36.880 --> 00:34:38.500
You were accessing i-Mode.

00:34:38.500 --> 00:34:39.800
And you had to like --

00:34:39.800 --> 00:34:41.570
if you prostrated before the
DOCOMO gods maybe you got

00:34:41.570 --> 00:34:42.870
in the i-Mode Menu.

00:34:42.870 --> 00:34:44.790
If you got in the i-Mode Menu,
then you were a billionaire.

00:34:44.790 --> 00:34:47.190
It's like -- there were all
these like weird gates to it.

00:34:47.190 --> 00:34:48.490
&gt;&gt; Virginia Heffernan: Uh-huh.

00:34:48.490 --> 00:34:51.000
&gt;&gt; Craig Mod: So the Internet
in Japan, and I'm by no means

00:34:51.000 --> 00:34:53.420
like an expert on the Internet
in Japan, but it kind of evolved

00:34:53.420 --> 00:34:58.590
in this weird way where in --
while we were embracing blogging

00:34:58.590 --> 00:35:01.720
with our -- not with
pseudonyms, you know.

00:35:01.720 --> 00:35:03.660
We were ourselves blogging.

00:35:03.660 --> 00:35:07.250
Blogging became a thing where, you
know, Kettley and others said, oh,

00:35:07.250 --> 00:35:09.010
hey, we can publish these folks.

00:35:09.010 --> 00:35:12.150
This is to your point about this
being real literature or not,

00:35:12.150 --> 00:35:15.160
being recognized as something
that can be made into book form

00:35:15.160 --> 00:35:16.460
that should be out there.

00:35:16.460 --> 00:35:18.610
These people should get a platform
outside of just the Internet.

00:35:18.610 --> 00:35:21.960
Japan kind of evolved in
this kind of funky way.

00:35:21.960 --> 00:35:25.100
And you had things like cell phone
novels which a lot of people point

00:35:25.100 --> 00:35:27.770
to which, by the way,
is totally not a thing.

00:35:27.770 --> 00:35:29.070
&gt;&gt; Sarah Burnes: So, yeah,

00:35:29.070 --> 00:35:31.080
because American publishers
are totally fascinated

00:35:31.080 --> 00:35:32.380
by that and want it --

00:35:32.380 --> 00:35:33.680
&gt;&gt; Craig Mod: It's like --

00:35:33.680 --> 00:35:34.980 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Sarah Burnes: -- oh, we'll do it.

00:35:34.980 --> 00:35:36.280
&gt;&gt; Craig Mod: -- for a millisecond.

00:35:36.280 --> 00:35:37.690
So one wrote up -- wrote a novel on
a cell phone and like someone wrote

00:35:37.690 --> 00:35:38.990
about it for the <i>New York Times </i>.

00:35:38.990 --> 00:35:40.490
And that was it forever
and ever [laughter].

00:35:40.490 --> 00:35:41.790
&gt;&gt; Robin Sloan: Yeah.

00:35:41.790 --> 00:35:43.190 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Craig Mod: Japan is the -- like
there are two fallacies about Japan.

00:35:43.190 --> 00:35:45.450
One is that it's technologically
advanced.

00:35:45.450 --> 00:35:46.750
It's totally not.

00:35:46.750 --> 00:35:50.170 position:56%
Everyone faxes things and, you
know, you go into government offices

00:35:50.170 --> 00:35:53.010
and it's like going back
into 1950 here in America.

00:35:53.010 --> 00:35:55.650
And cell phones have not
really evolved at all either.

00:35:55.650 --> 00:35:56.950
Everyone uses an iPhone now.

00:35:56.950 --> 00:35:58.250
That was really weird.

00:35:58.250 --> 00:36:01.190
iPhones sort of leapfrogging
everything in Japan much

00:36:01.190 --> 00:36:03.870
to the sadness of Sony
and Toshiba and Sharp.

00:36:03.870 --> 00:36:07.020
But then also the cell phone
novels really aren't anything.

00:36:07.020 --> 00:36:08.750
Japan is still -- Japan has not --

00:36:08.750 --> 00:36:11.960
they just got the Kindle
two-and-a-half years ago, right?

00:36:11.960 --> 00:36:13.730
So Japan's like six
years behind on Kindle.

00:36:13.730 --> 00:36:15.760
The publishers were
really against it.

00:36:15.760 --> 00:36:18.000
I've never seen a Kindle in public.

00:36:18.000 --> 00:36:19.300
&gt;&gt; Virginia Heffernan: Hmm.

00:36:19.300 --> 00:36:20.600
&gt;&gt; Sarah Burnes: Wow.

00:36:20.600 --> 00:36:21.900
&gt;&gt; Craig Mod: And then iBooks.

00:36:21.900 --> 00:36:23.870
I rarely see anyone using
an iPad to read books.

00:36:23.870 --> 00:36:26.290 position:56%
If they are, they're reading comics.

00:36:26.290 --> 00:36:31.280
And that's a pragmatic sort
of choice because comics,

00:36:31.280 --> 00:36:34.640
they're published weekly in these
things that are like 600 pages

00:36:34.640 --> 00:36:36.100
and they look like phonebooks.

00:36:36.100 --> 00:36:38.880 position:56%
And so, you know, 10 years ago
you'd have people reading phonebooks

00:36:38.880 --> 00:36:40.180
on the subway.

00:36:40.180 --> 00:36:41.480
And they're very disposable.

00:36:41.480 --> 00:36:43.460
You're through the phonebook
in, you know, a couple of hours.

00:36:43.460 --> 00:36:46.570
And so if you can do that on your
iPad that's a little bit nicer.

00:36:46.570 --> 00:36:49.050
But for the most part
bookstores are thriving.

00:36:49.050 --> 00:36:50.920
My neighborhood -- I moved in next

00:36:50.920 --> 00:36:52.220
to my favorite bookstore
in the world.

00:36:52.220 --> 00:36:55.680
It's the most profitable
bookstore in Japan right now.

00:36:55.680 --> 00:36:57.870
It opened three years ago,
three-and-a-half years ago.

00:36:57.870 --> 00:37:00.460
Just as Borders was closing
here, this bookstore was opening.

00:37:00.460 --> 00:37:01.760
This massive --

00:37:01.760 --> 00:37:03.060
&gt;&gt; Sarah Burnes: Is it
an independent store?

00:37:03.060 --> 00:37:04.360
&gt;&gt; Craig Mod: It's not.

00:37:04.360 --> 00:37:06.950
It was a DVD rental company --

00:37:06.950 --> 00:37:08.250
&gt;&gt; Sarah Burnes: Oh.

00:37:08.250 --> 00:37:09.550
&gt;&gt; Craig Mod: -- that
started doing bookstores.

00:37:09.550 --> 00:37:11.130
And they had this like -- this
idea of let's make this kind

00:37:11.130 --> 00:37:12.950
of shrine to books and magazines.

00:37:12.950 --> 00:37:14.250
&gt;&gt; Sarah Burnes: Mm-hmm.

00:37:14.250 --> 00:37:15.550
Sounds good.

00:37:15.550 --> 00:37:16.850
&gt;&gt; Craig Mod: And it
worked really well.

00:37:16.850 --> 00:37:22.590
And so the Internet in Japan and
literature kind of don't overlap

00:37:22.590 --> 00:37:23.890
that much in what I've seen.

00:37:23.890 --> 00:37:26.100
And one of my good friends,
Motoyuki Shibata is one

00:37:26.100 --> 00:37:30.930
of the pre-eminent translators
of American fiction to Japanese.

00:37:30.930 --> 00:37:33.440
He runs this great journal
called <i>Monkey Business </i>.

00:37:33.440 --> 00:37:35.270
In the States it's
<i>Monkey Business </i>.

00:37:35.270 --> 00:37:36.680
In Japan it's just called <i>Monkey </i>.

00:37:36.680 --> 00:37:39.010
And nothing is online.

00:37:39.010 --> 00:37:42.240
And they have all these
wonderful -- I keep poking him.

00:37:42.240 --> 00:37:44.570
I've been poking him for years
to get this stuff online.

00:37:44.570 --> 00:37:48.850
And there just isn't that
desire to get it up there.

00:37:48.850 --> 00:37:50.980 position:56%
So it's a very strange relationship.

00:37:50.980 --> 00:37:54.160
But Japan is still very,
very analog on a whole.

00:37:54.160 --> 00:37:55.460
&gt;&gt; Sarah Burnes: Yes.

00:37:55.460 --> 00:37:58.910
Would you like a mic?

00:37:58.910 --> 00:38:01.230
&gt;&gt; Well, I'll try to --

00:38:01.230 --> 00:38:02.530
&gt;&gt; Sarah Burnes: Yeah.

00:38:02.530 --> 00:38:03.830
Here comes -- here comes one.

00:38:03.830 --> 00:38:05.130
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:38:05.130 --> 00:38:07.430
&gt;&gt; I'm fascinated by --

00:38:11.110 --> 00:38:12.410
I'm Bob Darnton [assumed spelling].

00:38:12.410 --> 00:38:16.580
I was fascinated by Virginia
Heffernan's characterization

00:38:16.580 --> 00:38:21.170
of the <i>New Yorker </i>[laughter]
as a kind of writing that --

00:38:21.170 --> 00:38:24.440
from which you have been
liberated to the epitome

00:38:24.440 --> 00:38:28.640
of in a way overwriting
by minimizing.

00:38:28.640 --> 00:38:32.080
My statistics are probably wrong,

00:38:32.080 --> 00:38:38.810
but roughly 310,000 new books were
produced in the U.S. last year

00:38:38.810 --> 00:38:41.560
through the normal trade process.

00:38:41.560 --> 00:38:46.340
And something like 700,000
were self-published.

00:38:46.340 --> 00:38:47.640
&gt;&gt; Virginia Heffernan:
Amazing, yeah.

00:38:47.640 --> 00:38:50.900
&gt;&gt; The explosion of
self-publishing is amazing.

00:38:50.900 --> 00:38:55.070
I mean its authors
are now everywhere.

00:38:55.070 --> 00:38:57.760
Everyone is an author
as you were saying,

00:38:57.760 --> 00:39:00.560
and it has a kind of
liberating quality.

00:39:00.560 --> 00:39:03.410
So how to formulate
this as a question.

00:39:03.410 --> 00:39:06.850
The question is, what
is authorship now?

00:39:06.850 --> 00:39:12.210
The <i>New Yorker </i>no longer has
this ultimate seal of approval --

00:39:12.210 --> 00:39:13.510
&gt;&gt; Virginia Heffernan: Mm-hmm.

00:39:13.510 --> 00:39:15.550
&gt;&gt; -- and there is this liberating
effect that you described.

00:39:15.550 --> 00:39:17.040
It's fascinating to hear.

00:39:17.040 --> 00:39:19.240
So where are we going?

00:39:19.240 --> 00:39:23.640
Are we going to have a world
of different kinds of authors

00:39:23.640 --> 00:39:25.540
or everyone being an author?

00:39:25.540 --> 00:39:27.530
You know, it used to be said

00:39:27.530 --> 00:39:30.770
that books were written
for the general public.

00:39:30.770 --> 00:39:33.310
Now they're written
by the general public.

00:39:33.310 --> 00:39:34.610
&gt;&gt; Virginia Heffernan: Mm-hmm.

00:39:34.610 --> 00:39:39.220
&gt;&gt; So how do you understand this
kind of sociological transformation

00:39:39.220 --> 00:39:40.640
of the condition of the author?

00:39:40.640 --> 00:39:45.140 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Virginia Heffernan: I mean to
the extent that the word author has,

00:39:45.140 --> 00:39:48.140
you know, authority attached
to it, I do actually --

00:39:48.140 --> 00:39:51.690
you know, it's possible that there
will not -- that the terms --

00:39:51.690 --> 00:39:55.990
that literature and
authorship still belong

00:39:55.990 --> 00:40:01.390
to analog media and to print books.

00:40:01.390 --> 00:40:06.000
So I was in my more Bolshevik
for the Internet days

00:40:06.000 --> 00:40:09.400
when I was a real -- like I didn't
see anything wrong with like,

00:40:09.400 --> 00:40:11.880
you know, the way that
Sovietologists used to be

00:40:11.880 --> 00:40:15.410
like Europe will fall and we'll get
rid of all this and -- so that's --

00:40:15.410 --> 00:40:19.660
you know, I was like really
impatient with anyone who as

00:40:19.660 --> 00:40:21.760
like I don't want to
use a touchscreen.

00:40:21.760 --> 00:40:23.650
I was just like you better
get used to it [laughter].

00:40:23.650 --> 00:40:29.060
I was on a panel with someone who's
not like that, Nicholson Baker,

00:40:29.060 --> 00:40:33.950 position:56%
who objects so much to digitization
that he even wanted the card catalog

00:40:33.950 --> 00:40:37.730
to be preserved just like --
it's a natural for digitization,

00:40:37.730 --> 00:40:39.460
frankly, like a numerical system.

00:40:39.460 --> 00:40:42.540
But, you know, he missed
the cards and so forth.

00:40:42.540 --> 00:40:46.220
And, you know, I was talking very
excitedly about self-publishing,

00:40:46.220 --> 00:40:48.170
a lot of which, you know --

00:40:48.170 --> 00:40:51.700 position:56%
I was talking first about publishing
moving to e-books and how great

00:40:51.700 --> 00:40:54.050
that was and how we weren't
going to lose anything.

